attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB pie executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, BuildID[sha1]=925afcc7c3ae10e2d9a62c0104b0448571b27b64, for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The sample is a Linux backdoor. It daemonizes itself, renames its process using `prctl` for evasion, and establishes persistence through various methods, including creating files in `/.config` and likely manipulating system services (inferred from decrypted strings). The malware gathers system information (`uname`) and user details (`getpwuid`), then connects to a C2 server. It can receive commands to execute arbitrary shell commands (`sh -c`) or to spawn a reverse shell (`sub_407028`), giving the attacker full control. Many of its strings are XOR-obfuscated with the key 0xaf.
